  <assign id="22">
    <name>Assignment #2: Differentiate one of your writing lessons</name>
    <intro>&lt;p&gt;Rework one of your lessons through the lens of Gradual Release and differentiated instruction. Consider how you might adapt the &lt;b&gt;content&lt;/b&gt;, &lt;b&gt;process&lt;/b&gt;, and/or &lt;b&gt;product. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Write a plan&lt;/b&gt; for a specified group of learners in your class (a group of two or three students). Describe the learners briefly by their interests, learning profiles, and levels of readiness.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Consider how you can add choices:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="line-height: 1.231;"&gt;If your lesson objective is a skill or a process (e.g., sentence combining or calculating sale item discounts), allow learners to choose the content.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="line-height: 1.231;"&gt;If your lesson objective is content specific (e.g., social studies), allow learners to choose the tools and media for submission (on paper, via blog, audio recording).&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="line-height: 1.231;"&gt;If your lesson is product specific (e.g., an essay), allow learners to choose the content (topic) or media for submission.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;How will these adaptations affect your ongoing monitoring of learner progress? What will success look like? Are your expectations high enough?&lt;/p&gt;</intro>
